===Etymology 1===
{{etyl|enm}} {{term|penne|penne|enclosure for animals|lang=enm}} from {{etyl|ang}} {{term|penn|penn-|enclosure|lang=ang}} (in compounds) from {{proto|Germanic|penn-|to bolt, pin, nail, secure|lang=en}} from {{proto|Indo-European|bend-|pointed peg, nail, edge|lang=en}}. Akin to {{etyl|ang|-}} {{term|pennian|-pennian|to close, lock, bolt|lang=ang}} (in compounds) (compare {{term|onpennian|onpennian|to open|lang=ang}}), {{etyl|nds|-}} {{term|pennen|pennen|to secure a door with a bolt|lang=nds}}, {{etyl|ang|-}} {{term|pinn|pinn|peg, bolt|lang=ang}}. More at {{term|pin|lang=en}}.

Sense “prison” originally figurative extension to enclosure for persons (1845), later influenced by {{term|penitentiary||prison|lang=en}}, being analyzed as an abbreviation (1884).<ref name="oetyld">{{R:Online Etymology Dictionary}}</ref>

